      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Versioning and Reproducibility"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Snapshotting the Eval Set"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Snap the eval set to a version tag before each model release. This lets you reproduce any historical CI run and compare model versions against the same fixed set of cases:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Snapshot eval set at a version tag before each release\nimport subprocess, json\n\ndef snapshot_eval_set(version_tag: str, split: str = \"dev\") -> str:\n    \"\"\"Export eval cases to a versioned JSONL file and push to artifact store.\"\"\"\n    cases = fetch_eval_cases(split=split, min_version=None)\n    filename = f\"eval_cases_{version_tag}_{split}.jsonl\"\n    with open(filename, \"w\") as f:\n        for case in cases:\n            f.write(json.dumps(case) + \"\\n\")\n\n    # Tag the git commit with the eval set version\n    subprocess.run([\"git\", \"tag\", f\"eval/{version_tag}\"], check=True)\n    subprocess.run([\"git\", \"push\", \"origin\", f\"eval/{version_tag}\"], check=True)\n\n    # Upload JSONL to artifact store (S3, GCS, etc.)\n    upload_artifact(filename, f\"eval-sets/{version_tag}/{filename}\")\n    return filename\n\n# Run before every model candidate release\n# snapshot_eval_set(version_tag=\"v2024-06-15\", split=\"dev\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Regression Tracking"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Beyond pass-rate thresholds, track regressions explicitly: cases that passed on the baseline model but fail on the candidate. A single regression in a confirmed-hard case should block the PR regardless of aggregate scores:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Detect regressions: cases that passed in baseline but fail in candidate\nimport pandas as pd\n\ndef find_regressions(\n    baseline_results: list[dict],\n    candidate_results: list[dict],\n) -> list[dict]:\n    base_df = pd.DataFrame(baseline_results).set_index(\"case_id\")\n    cand_df = pd.DataFrame(candidate_results).set_index(\"case_id\")\n\n    # Regressions: passed in baseline, failed in candidate\n    regressions = cand_df[~cand_df[\"pass\"] & base_df[\"pass\"]]\n\n    # Improvements: failed in baseline, passed in candidate\n    improvements = cand_df[cand_df[\"pass\"] & ~base_df[\"pass\"]]\n\n    print(f\"Regressions: {len(regressions)}, Improvements: {len(improvements)}\")\n    return regressions.reset_index().to_dict(orient=\"records\")\n\n# A single regression in the 'regression' category blocks the PR.\n# Regressions in 'style' are flagged but not blocking."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Operational Considerations"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Eval set staleness: ",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Refresh the eval set at least monthly by adding new feedback-derived cases. An eval set that hasn't grown in 90 days is likely measuring yesterday's failure modes, not today's."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Scorer drift: ",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "LLM judges change behaviour as their underlying models are updated. Pin the judge model version in eval configuration and re-validate judge agreement with human scores quarterly."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Cost control: ",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "For large eval suites (> 1000 cases), cache judge responses keyed by (case_id, model_id, response_hash). Identical responses don't need re-judging. Cache TTL should be one model release cycle."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Flaky eval cases: ",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Cases where judge scores vary across runs (standard deviation > 0.2) are noisy and should be removed or rewritten with a tighter rubric. Treat flaky eval cases like flaky tests: fix or delete them."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Blind test set hygiene: ",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Never use the "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "test",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " split during development. If a developer looks at test-split failures while iterating, the set is contaminated and its scores no longer represent out-of-distribution performance."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Summary"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Eval integration closes the loop between user feedback and model deployment. Reviewed production failures become versioned eval cases with machine-readable rubrics, stored in a growing eval set split into dev (PR gates) and test (release certification). An LLM-as-judge runner scores candidate model responses against each case, and a CI gate with category-specific thresholds blocks regressions before they reach production. Version-tag eval sets before each release, track regressions explicitly, and refresh the set monthly to keep it aligned with current failure modes."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}